🎬 Act I: The Fundamentals
Before writing Grid code, you need to understand the relationship between the Grid Parent (Container) and the Grid Children (Items).

To turn any HTML element into a grid, you simply apply:

CSS
.container {
    display: grid;
}
1. Columns and Rows
You define the structure of your grid using grid-template-columns and grid-template-rows.

CSS
.container {
    display: grid;
    /* Creates 3 columns: 200px wide, 400px wide, and 100px wide */
    grid-template-columns: 200px 400px 100px;
    
    /* Creates 2 rows: 150px tall and 300px tall */
    grid-template-rows: 150px 300px;
}
2. The fr (Fractional) Unit
Forget percentages! The fr unit represents a fraction of the available free space in the grid container. It automatically recalculates when the screen resizes.

CSS
.container {
    /* Splits the screen into 3 equal columns */
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; 
    
    /* The middle column takes twice as much space as the sides */
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr; 
}
3. Gaps (Spacing)
Instead of fighting with margins on individual items, you can set spacing directly on the parent.

CSS
.container {
    column-gap: 20px; /* Space between columns */
    row-gap: 15px;    /* Space between rows */
    gap: 20px 15px;   /* Shorthand: row-gap column-gap */
}
🎬 Act II: Power Utilities (repeat & minmax)
Writing out 1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr gets exhausting. Grid comes with built-in functions to make your code cleaner and fully responsive.

1. The repeat() Function
Duplicating tracks is incredibly easy:

CSS
.container {
    /* Exactly the same as writing 1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr */
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr); 
}
2. The minmax() Function
This prevents elements from getting too small or too large. It accepts two parameters: minmax(MIN, MAX).

CSS
.container {
    /* Row is at least 100px tall, but expands if text overflows */
    grid-template-rows: minmax(100px, auto); 
}
3. Responsive Layouts Without Media Queries (auto-fit / auto-fill)
Combine repeat and minmax to create a wrapping card grid that automatically adapts to any screen size without a single media query:

CSS
.card-grid {
    display: grid;
    /* Create as many columns as fit, minimum 250px wide, maximum 1fr */
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
    gap: 20px;
}
🎬 Act III: Positioning Child Elements
By default, items drop sequentially into the grid cells. However, you can force grid items to stretch across multiple rows or columns using Grid Lines.

CSS
.featured-card {
    /* Starts at column line 1, spans across to line 3 */
    grid-column-start: 1;
    grid-column-end: 3;

    /* Shorthand for the exact same thing: */
    grid-column: 1 / 3; 

    /* Alternative shorthand: start here, span 2 tracks */
    grid-column: 1 / span 2; 
    
    /* Make it span multiple rows */
    grid-row: 1 / 4; 
}
🎬 Act IV: Grid Template Areas (The Visual Layout Method)
If you hate counting grid lines, you can map your layout visually in pure text using grid-template-areas.

Step 1: Name the items
CSS
header { grid-area: header; }
sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
main { grid-area: main; }
footer { grid-area: footer; }
Step 2: Draw the layout on the parent
CSS
.wrapper {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 3fr;
    grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
    grid-template-areas: 
        "header  header"
        "sidebar main"
        "footer  footer";
    height: 100vh;
}
🎬 Act V: Grid vs. Flexbox (When to use what?)
Use Flexbox (1D) when you are aligning items in a single direction (either a row or a column). Perfect for navigation bars, buttons alignment, or simple rows.

Use Grid (2D) when you need to align items in both rows and columns simultaneously. Perfect for full-page layouts, image galleries, and complex dashboard interfaces.